The Darkest Days Of Winter The middle of winter has long been a time of celebration around the world. Centuries before the arrival of the man called Jesus, early Europeans celebrated light and birth in the darkest days of winter. Many peoples rejoiced during the winter solstice, when the worst of the winter was behind them and they could look forward to longer days and extended hours of sunlight. In Scandinavia, the Norse celebrated Yule from December 21, the winter solstice, through January. In recognition of the return of the sun, fathers and sons would bring home large logs, which they would set on fire. The people would feast until the log burned out, which could take as many as 12 days. The Norse believed that each spark from the fire represented a new pig or calf that would be born during the coming year. ----- Full article here. @ChristianityExposed

The next time you hear a murder of crows cackling for no apparent reason, show a little respect: You may have stumbled onto a crow funeral. Crows are among the few animals that exhibit a social response to a dead member of their species. Though their caws may sound like heartbroken cries, such funerals aren't so much about mourning their fallen friends as they are about learning from their mistakes. Murders will surround a dead member of the group to see what killed it and how to stay away from it. Flocking into a large, noisy group provides them protection from the threat if it's still around. Crows have been also known to nurse and spread grudges, sometimes dive-bombing people that have harmed one of their own.

The Maypoleâ€“ A Traditional May Day Symbol May 1st is an ancient Northern Hemisphere festival, now known as May Day, which traditionally marked the return of summer. It is believed that the celebrations originated in agricultural rituals intended to ensure fertility of crops. Later developments included the Celtic festival of Beltane and the Germanic festival of Walpurgis Night. Today, many customs still mark this ancient festival, including the gathering of wildflowers and the setting up of a decorated May tree or Maypole, around which people dance. No one can say for certain how Maypoles came to be, but they may have been inspired by Norse beliefs in the world tree, Yggdrasil, or Germanic pagan reverence for trees. Traditionally, participants dance around a wooden Maypole while holding colorful ribbons that become decoratively intertwined. The dancers then change direction and repeat the steps in reverse, causing the ribbons to unwind. This is said to symbolize the lengthening of the days as summer begins.

Easter shows its pagan origins in a dating system based on the lunar calendar. It is fixed as the first Sunday after the first Full Moon following the Equinox (Spring Equinox in the Northern Hemisphere where the festival originated). The festival is named after Ostara, the Saxon goddess of spring, the dawn and fertility. Symbols of fertility and new life such as eggs and rabbits became associated with the new growth of the season. Ostaraâ€™s familiar, the Moon Hare was spellbound by the lunar glow and is now known as the Easter Bunny. The eating of hot crossed buns was also an ancient pagan tradition, the cross representing the four quarters of the moon. Christian myth dated the resurrection of christ during this festival of rebirth. In Australia, Easter remains one of the few community celebrations honouring ancient pagan symbolism. West Wycombe Park is a country house near the village of West Wycombe in Buckinghamshire, England, built between 1740 and 1800. It was conceived as a pleasure palace for the 18th-century libertine and dilettante Sir Francis Dashwood, 2nd Baronet. The house is a long rectangle with four faÃ§ades that are columned and pedimented, three theatrically so. The house encapsulates the entire progression of British 18th-century architecture from early idiosyncratic Palladian to the Neoclassical, although anomalies in the design of the house also make it architecturally unique. The mansion is set within an 18th-century landscaped park containing many small temples and follies, which act as satellites to the greater temple, the house.

Hahnenklee Stave Church The church was built in 1907-1908 over a period of ten months. The model was the much older stave churches in Norway. The local craftsmen used spruce wood from the area as building material, which also made the construction more cost-effective than the originally planned neo-Gothic brick building. Many elements of the building style are reminiscent of shipbuilding, and also somewhat of Viking ships with the numerous dragons on the roof and in the decorations. The chandelier is modeled on a ship's wheel. The design of the altar in particular combines the Art Nouveau style, which was popular at the time of construction, with elements of Byzantine art. On one side there is a depiction of a man attacking another with what looks like a donkeyâ€™s jaw-bone, while a woman sits in the background. This would appear to be Samson attacking a Philistine, while the woman might be his would-be bride, watching from a distance. The western face has a spiral swastika-like symbol, the closest parallels of which are found on stone carvings from northern Iberia, as well as scenes depicting the Virgin Mary, a stag hunt, and a chariot procession. The cap-stone at the top has depictions of Noah and John the Baptist. At the base of the cross is an inscription in Old Irish: Or Do Maelsechnaill (â€œa prayer for Maelsechnaillâ€). This is a reference to MÃ¡el Sechnaill, son of MÃ¡el Ruanaid, who ruled as High King of Ireland between AD 846 and AD 862. The Moylough Belt Shrine, found in a peat-bog near Moylough, in county Sligo, Ireland; 8th century AD. ğŸ‡®ğŸ‡ª This belt-shrine is the only known example of its type. It is made from bronze and leather, with enamel and glass inlays, and silver plates. It is decorated in insular La TÃ¨ne style, while typologically the belt itself is most similar to Frankish and Burgundian belts of the same period. The belt was almost certainly a relic of a Christian saint, perhaps the leather sections having been extracted from the original belt and embellished afterward with the metal, glass, and enamel components. New project is live: a folk music channel. The aim is for it to be a digital radio with ancient and beautiful songs. It came about because admin felt a strong urge to listen to folk music, having particular admiration for Finnish, Norwegian and Latvian music of the sort, but not finding anything like it already on TG. Admin spots are open, especially if you know a bit about folk music or are interested in looking into folk music from your culture. It is likely to be a tough project and Iâ€™ve wanted to start it for a while, but it seemed almost impossible, with the language barriers, it being hard to find recordings of some songs or there being many renditions of the same song and having to choose just one to post. But it is surely better to begin the project than thinking itâ€™s too hard. Hopefully others will find it worthwhile too. Feel free to spam @swastikafolkchat with music files, even if they are not necessarily true folk songs. The channel however will only contain authentic folk songs. https://t.me/swastikafolk

The Nibelungenhalle, i.e. the Hall of the Nibelungs, is a domed structure in Koenigswinter, (North Rhine-Westphalia, Rhine-Sieg). The Hall of the Nibelungs was opened on Richard Wagner's hundredth birthday, in 1913. The idea of the structure is the merit of the artist Hermann Hendrich, it was realized by Berlin architects Hans Mayer and Werner Behrendt. The building was built in the Art Nouveau style. In 1933, a "Dragon's Den" was built outside the structure, a hall with reptiles - a terrarium. You can see all the splendor and symbolism of this structure in these photos. @Odal24

Scythian and Greek warriors covered in swastikas, solar crosses, and eight-pointed stars with grazing horses by Exekias 550-525 BCE. Found in Orvieto, Etruscan era, but believed to be of Greek manufacture. I had a real time trying to find hi-res images of this. "With good pasture land at a premium, horses remained synonymous with wealth throughout all of Greek history. They were used principally for the essentially upperclass pastimes of hunting and racing in peacetime and for cavalry service during wartime. During the Trojan War the Homeric heroes on both sides rode into battle in two-horse chariots and exchanged horses as high-status gifts. At the beginning of the 6th century BC the second class of citizens in Athens, the Hippeis (meaning "Knights"), were required to own horses and to serve in the cavalry. The cavalryÂ´s role remained fundamental to Greek military tactics until the end of antiquity..." Read more: https://paganimagevault.blogspot.com/2022/10/scythian-and-greek-warriors-covered-in.html

American frontier mothers ingeniously converted the ancient good luck sign into a quilt pattern which is made simply from two triangles. These piece together so rapidly that even beginners love it. They commonly called it the Fly Foot pattern, a corruption of the ancient Anglo Saxon name Fylfot. According to old-time quilters, it makes a quilt "hard to beat." Swastika motifs were some of the best-loved quilting patterns and are still popular in more disguised variations. These have been given colourful folsky names such as Wonder of the World, Whirligig, Pinwheel, Plumed Swastika, Catch-Me-If-You-Can, Chinese 10,000 Perfections, Battle Axe of Thor, Heart's seal, Wind Power of the Osage, Twist and Turn, Mound Builders, Follow-the-Leader, as well as: Quilt patterns, clockwise from top left: Merry-go-round; Monkey Wrench; Pinwheel; Fly Foot; Walking Triangles; Mrs. Morgan's Choice; See Saw; Bow Knot; Crazy Ann; Yankee Puzzle; Next Door Neighbour; Lindbergh's Propeller. Ceremonial standard from Anatolia, early bronze age, late 3rd Millenium BC. Burial item found in AlajahÃ¶yuk archeological site. These standards had a stem at the base where a handle could be inserted, suggesting they were a ritual item. The standard, which is a diagonal square, has a single swastika pattern attached to the top and left and right corners in a rectangular shape. Each swastika is inside a rectangle and four are lined up vertically and horizontally. Moreover, each of the swastika's four arms is the connected to the arm of the adjacent figure. "Strangely, such a pattern in which swastikas in a rectangle are connected to top, bottom, left, and right swastikas cannot be found anywhere else, but in Japan, it is found in the patterns on the clothes of Buddhist statues." 'Hymn to the Rose', 1907 John Duncan Duncan was born in Dundee in 1866, the son of a cattleman. John, however, had no interest in the family business and preferred the visual arts. By the age of 11 he was a student at the Dundee School of Art, then based at the High School of Dundee. Called a madman by some and a mystic by others, Duncan admitted to hearing 'faerie music' whilst he painted. Although his work remains strongly rooted in the Pre-Raphaelite movement, there is a certain graphical quality which sets it apart from his contemporaries and likens it to Art Nouveau, while the subject matter is thoroughly Celtic Revival; he is generally referred to as a "symbolist" by art critics.

Russian Ruble banknotes issued in 1918 by the provisional government, in circulation until 1922. The government after the revolution did not intend to use the swastika, they simply used banknotes that had already been printed in 1917 before the abdication as they had to issue currency and lacked production ability. The symbol was subsequently banned by either Lev Trotsky or Lunacharsky in 1922 or 1923. It is not unlikely that Empress Alexandra Feodorovna might have had something to do with the design of the banknotes since she was particularly fond of the å and endless knot symbols.

The basement of Ipatiev house where the Russian Imperial family were massacred. The wallpaper is adorned with a symbol which looks like the squatter man/Bengali swastika/Thunderbolt symbol/Pisces symbol/Variation of the Chinese or asian Shou symbol/Berber "Free Man" symbol. The Empress drew a swastika on a door jamb and above the bed headboard of the Tsar before they were killed in this basement adorned with the â€˜Bengali swastikaâ€™. Rather eerie. It is interesting to note that the Imperial family, especially the Empress, were big fans of the symbol. They were killed in 1917. In 1920 the symbol was first used in an NSDAP setting. The endless knot or eternal knot (sanskrit: srivatsa; simplified chinese: ; traditional chinese: ; pinyin: panzhang jie; tibetan dpal be'u; mongolian ) is a symbolic knot and one of the eight auspicious symbols. It is an important symbol in hinduism, jainism and buddhism. It is an important cultural marker in places significantly influenced by tibetan buddhism such as tibet, mongolia, tuva, kalmykia, and buryatia. It is also found in celtic and chinese symbolism. A tapestry (Finnish: ryijy) with a large TursaansydÃ¤n ('heart of Tursas'; a å within a +), a sacred symbol of good luck, 1823. A ryijy is a woven Finnish long-tufted tapestry or knotted-pile carpet. In medieval times these valuable items were mostly used as bedcovers with the tuft side down, and their decorations were few and simple. Later they were used the other way around, and the decorations became more elaborate. Two-sided ryijys would have been decorated only on one side. In the 1700s decorative ryijys became common among ordinary people, who would display them on festive occasions, and a special ryijy was used in wedding ceremonies, then later as a bedcover by the newlyweds. In the era of national romanticism the ryijy became primarily a decorative tapestry. Photo: The National Museum of Finland

It makes you think when you realise that the swastika was not merely aesthetic, but for thousands if not tens of thousands of years was indeed related to the divine, to rituals, talismans, cults, religions, prophecies and rich metaphysical viewpoints. Now, it is something half of the world has turned their back on, that makes many recoil, imbuing them with negative feelings. Relegated to the â€™occultâ€™, itâ€™s meaning is all but lost, and already, for hundreds of years merely a faint ghost remains of itâ€™s meaning and, with a seemingly tragic turn of luck, those places and people who still barely held on to these ghosts of meaning have suffered particularly devastating losses to their culture: Finland, Native America, Tibet, Russia, Armenia, Yugoslavia just to name a few and also Germany, Friesland, Greece and in fact a great deal of Europe and far beyond. Through the aftermath of the last war, these ancient cultures have had something precious and ancient taken out of them, replaced with an arguably lesser new order of being. If you consider the possibility that the Christian cross would be â€˜cancelledâ€™ in such a way due to some actions by Christians in the past, imagine the uproar it would cause. Yet, a symbol far older and more widespread in the ancient past has been all but deleted, just like that. The first time the swastika was made illegal was by Trotsky in 1923, presumably as part of the Communist fight against old ways and religions. Who really is at fault for deleting such an epic and ancient symbol? The communists, Hitler, victors of the war, ourselves? Whatever the case, it must be remembered that there is no need to â€˜reclaimâ€™ the symbol, for it is a Human Heritage and can never be taken away, perhaps only in the minds of men. The shamans in the mountains of Tibet ascribe their name for the symbol as meaning unborn, undying. This symbol can never truly die in our minds and souls. It is remembered as being on the chest of Shiva and the Buddha, as a counterpart to the sun and the moon, as the banner of Lamas, Genghis Khan and Baron Ungern Sternberg, as a holy prophetic symbol that shows the way from the watery underworld for the American Indians; as a symbol of reincarnation, renaissance and ressurection for the Armenians and all those who used it on funerary items, gravestones and tombs; as a symbol related to Greek as well as Celtic, Scandinavian, Indian, Baltic and Finnish Gods and Goddesses; as an imagery form depicting the transformation of the power of the Sun into the power of the seer, with arms extending towards the four cardinal directions and engulfing all space; as associated with the Seven Sages (Saptarishi), the Great Bear and the eternal revolution around a fixed aim; as thunderbolts and the Chariot of Helios. A symbol of eternity, immutability and imperishability, it will forever await in the depths of our mind and the heart of the sea, in the patterns and cycles of nature, in the hair whorls of cows and in the sky and the stars.

German Allach Earthenware Pitcher, 1935 Brown earthenware milk pitcher that measures 8 x 12" with a swastika motif. Allach Porcelain Manufacturing was established as a private concern in 1935 in the small town of Allach, near Munich, Germany. Acquired the following year by the SS, Heinrich Himmler had several goals in mind: he would produce art symbolic of German culture and simultaneously it could also be a source of income in the porcelain market. Himmler also had Allach produce gifts and awards for use of the Reich, and objects for his Aryan mysticism/paganism. And in the long term, Himmler hoped to influence German culture through the arts.

When the first Navajo man and woman emerged from the underworld called The Third World, a water world, they bore a son. A few years later, the son was so intrigued about the stories he had heard about the underworld that he went back to the place of emergence and while looking down fell in. His father then went after him to rescue his son among the endless rivers of the underworld. After uniting there, they were thrown into a long and perilous journey where they experienced and learned the heritage and lessons of Navajo medicine, which all had originated there. At the completion of their journey, harboring all of this valuable knowledge, they were attempting to exit the underworld when they were attacked by The Water Monsters. Just as the father and son were about to perish, two logs formed a cross in the water and four Yeis (holy messengers) appeared at the tips of the logs, forming a swastika-like shape. Geometric patterns fill the wide area around the deer silhouette: a swastika, series of angular lines, stars, chains of connected squares etc. Ca. 750 - 735 BC From Athens

Attic LGP Pottery - Trefoil oinochoe The upper, and main, picture shows a nude male figure, with a bird perching on his head, holding the reins of two horses which flank him. The two magnificent animals tower above the male figure. A swastika above the horses' backs, and a circle surrounded by dots with a line in the center, under their bellies, are used as fill patterns. In this Attic context it is likely that the painter gives to this character a heroic or aristocratic status by association with the pair of horses.

On the patterns of belts, you can often see a swastika, which came to the Old Believers from the local Komi - they adopted this ornament from the Ugrians in the Middle Ages, and the Ugrians, in turn, from the Indo-Iranians in the Bronze Age. For example, in the photo above, on the left, there is a belt with a swastika pattern from a private collection. To the right of it is the prayer dress of the Old Believers of the Verkhokamye of the Pomor and Fedoseevsky accords: a shirt-"sleeves" made of dark cotton and a black satin sundress dubas, trimmed along the edge with red fabric - a distinctive feature of the prayer sundress. This khagangma, or Tibetan seating square, is simply nothing short of an extraordinary example of Tibetan woven art. Stunningly beautiful, relatively large and in unaltered original condition, it has a central yundrung (swastika) motif and multiple borders all made with spectacular, highly saturated, natural dyes. The inner four corner fret designs are of a fascinating and unique rare purple shade - not dye run from the surrounding red colour â€“ which is also highly saturated, while the green used throughout is beautifully abrashed. The central green swastika, a symbol of power down though the millennia, is surrounded by a mandala-like circle of blue fret work, which upon closer inspection, is itself embedded in a burnt orange circle of wool, quite distinct from the red background (see circular close up above). The outer border is the â€˜running tâ€™ or â€˜Greek tâ€™ design in red embedded upon a magnificent, wonderfully abrashed, green. This piece would almost certainly have been used in a monastic setting. Source

Awa Odori - Dance of the Fools, Japan Awa Odori takes place during the Buddhist observance of O-bon, when the spirits of the dead are thought to return to their ancestral homes. In Tokushima the departed are welcomed back with a performance of the Dance of the Fools, which dates back more than 400 years. In 1587 a feudal overlord decided to throw a party to celebrate the completion of his new castle. His guests got so drunk that they began to dance, arms and legs flailing about all over the place. Once they had recovered from their hangovers it was decided to make it an annual event. The feudal government of the time, afraid that the gatherings could easily turn into a mob that would try and oust them from power, imposed restrictions on Awa Odori. Yet their legislation was unable to subdue the joyous spirit of the people, and the tradition lived on.

Latvia (weaving, knitting) Spain (embroidery) Bulgaria (embroidery) Mongolia, Tibet, Nepal (weaving and more) Roman (usually linen clothes with swastikas) India (I've seen it on sarees and other clothing) It's very likely that places such as Denmark, Faroe islands, Gotland, Ã…land, Poland and other places in the Baltic also had a tradition of incorporating swastika in textiles but I haven't come across anything from there yet.

It is interesting to note that there is a rare but modern pattern similar to the Gravettian 'protoswastika' pattern. There is also a swastika variation that has another turn or more in the ends. Bottom pictures are a tissue fragment found in Novgorod and dated to the 13th century and a reconstruction of the pattern. I think this pattern is great because if you look at the white swastikas in image 2, you see a simple swastika, but look at the red swastikas and you see a totally different pattern and both of these fit together. Pattern recreation is by Alexander Yakovlevich Kolesnikov. In 1974-1985 he went on an expedition to the Arkhangelsk, Pskov, Novgorod, Vologda, Kostroma, Yaroslavl, Ivanovo and Nizhny Novgorod regions in search of ancient patterns.

St Patrickâ€™s Bell shrine The external shrine was commissioned by King Domnall Ua Lochlainn between 1091 and 1105. The front and sides, along with the entirety of crest show liberal use of â€˜Urnes styleâ€™ serpentine forms, indicating a significant Viking artistic influence. In the back panel (here pictured) is a 3D effect is conjured up through the use of a silver grille set over a sheet of gilded bronze. The repeated use of equal-armed Greek crosses formed in the voids of the silver grille forms 37 clockwise-spinning swastikas from solid silver in the junctions between the Greek crosses. The border is completed through the inclusion of 10 tau crosses, along with two L-shapes.

The Ardagh Chalice Ardagh, Co Limerick, Ireland Created during the 8th century, it bears a large amount of intricate and detailed decoration on its various elements. In particular, the two curving panels on the underside of the foot-ring. Each panel bears 72 incised Tau shapes, arranged in 18 groups of four. Each group of four produces a swastika shape at their intersection. Thus, there are 36 swastikas between the two panels. I only have an image of one of these panels, so canâ€™t be sure of the directionality of the entire set. The 18 swastikas are all rotating clockwise.

A penannular brooch from Lagore, Co. Meath, Ireland, dating to the 6th or 7th century. The published description indicates that the right-hand terminal is decorated with three chequerboard plaques of millefiori set in a red enamel background. The decorative elements are completed by the addition of a fourth blue and white millefiori plaque, this time bearing four swastikas. The two on the left turn anti clockwise, while the two on the right turn in the opposite direction. Each swastika is set within the quadrants of a pair of lines intersecting in an x-shape.

At Cathedral Hill, Co Armagh, Ireland, excavation by Cynthia Gaskell Brown and A.E.T. Harper in 1968 recovered a bone knife handle from a dump of material, pushed into a ditch. Judging by the associated material, it would appear to date to the broad period from the 5th to 10th centuries. It is also decorated with four swastikas, each one composed of simple, incised lines, enhanced by an incised outline, giving the whole the form of a small square.

The Hildesheim Cope 1310-1320 Germany/Saxony This cope has a fascinating, albeit gruesome, depiction of saints undergoing various forms of martyrdom. All sorts of infamous medieval torture methods are represented such as flaying (of St Bartholomew), roasting (of St Lawrence), several crucifixions (among others St Peter), variations of stabbings, clubbings and beheadings (most famously St Thomas Becket). Each saint is within a roundel. These roundels intersect with each other so as to form six-pointed star shapes, separated by spaces between the points of oval shape. In these small spaces there are blue dragons with red wings and at each point of the star shape are appliqued golden rosettes. Embroidery in polychrome silks and couched gold thread, entirely covers the linen background. Compared with known examples of contemporary Opus Anglicanum, this German work is rather naive and not as finely executed. Source

Rank badge, Korea 1850-1900 This rank badge (hyungbae in Korean) features a pair of black and white leopards, one above the other in opposing stance, surrounded by stylised cloud patterns in pink, purple and pale green upon a blue background. Between the paired animals is a trip-part eum-yang (yin-yang) symbol in blue, yellow and pink. Below are rocks and multi-coloured rainbow patterns with a central swastika. Hyungbae featuring leopards were worn exclusively by military officials. Those with two leopards signified that the wearer belonged to the first to third military ranks. The rank badge dates to the late Choson kingdom (1392-1910).

NSDAP Spanish Cross in bronze With the outbreak of the Spanish Civil War in July 1936 the Germans supported the Nationalist Falangist Generalissimo Francisco Franco against the communist allied Republican Loyalist party. The German support consisted of assorted field equipment and weapons, the Imker-Gruppe of ground personnel which included the Drohne-Gruppe of Panzer units and a group of Luftwaffe volunteers designated as the Condor Legion. The participation in this conflict enabled the Germans to test their fledgling armed forces and by rotating personnel gave them a core of troops with actual combat experience. With the successful conclusion of the Spanish Civil War at the end of March 1939 the German contingent returned home, to be heralded as heroes and on April 14TH 1939 Hitler instituted the Spanish Cross series of awards to recognize the service of the German volunteers in Spain. The award was introduced in three classes, bronze, silver and gold, and a special class of gold with swords and diamonds.

From the Himalaya Mountains, this very special yak horn is mounted in golden copper/embossed bronze with a small funnel at the end to fill the horn. The horn is used to carry a drink, the Chaang, which is a Tibetan beer brewed from barley grains and rice. Particularly popular amongst the Himalaya's inhabitants, this beer has a relatively weak alcohol grade and it is supposed to alleviate the severe cold of the Himalayan mountains. Putin Swag Rare photos from 2007, horse-riding in the Western Sayan Mountains. Swastikas and Horses have a very long history. It is said that the Quadriga chariot pulled by 4 horses is a representation of the swastika and 4 horse head swastikas were also very common in pagan Eastern Europe. Swastika decorations on horses survived in recent times in the Roman Empire, where many horse head swastika broches are found, as well as swastika spurs and depictions of Helios being carried across the sky by a 4 horse quadriga. The swastika-horse tradition perhaps started with the horse-riding Scythians and the Mongols, with both of these groups using the swastika heavily. The swastika was also used in Russia a lot especially between the 12th and 17th century and more recently and also lastly (discounting fake organizations like Ynglism in Russia and AllatRa in Ukraine), by the last members of the Russian Royal family. Bronze buckle. 5-6th century BC. The Kazbek treasure is a complex of bronze, silver, and iron objects numbering about 200 pieces, discovered in 1877 by G. D. Filimonov on the territory of the Kazbek station of the Georgian Military Road. The articles that have been dated include silver goblets and the figurine of a ram, executed in the style of the Achaemenid art of the sixth or fifth century B.c. Objects belonging to the late stage of the Koban culture are bronze vessels, fibulae, figurines of deer, phallic representations of man, hilts and their parts, bronze belts, and iron swords, spears, and bits. The Kazbek treasure is connected with the religious cults of the ancient tribes of the Caucasus. The principal part of the treasure is housed in the State Historical Museum in Moscow; the remainder is in the State Museum of Georgia in TbilisI.
